-- Binani, Mahindra and Reliance: India Equity Preview (Correct)
-- Pooja Thakur
-- 2010-06-17T04:51:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-17/cairn-cipla-mahindra-gammon-binani-tata-motors-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             (Corrects company name in Reliance item.)  
 The following companies may have
unusual price changes in India trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close.  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex,
gained 50.04, or 0.3 percent, to 17,462.87, the S&P CNX Nifty
Index on the National Stock Exchange rose 0.2 percent to
5,233.35 and the BSE 200 Index increased 0.2 percent to 2,209.16.
SGX CNX Nifty Index futures for June delivery added 0.2 to
5,231.5 at 10:47 a.m. in Singapore.  
 Binani Cement Ltd. (BINC IN): The cement maker plans to buy
back 14.5 million of its shares at 90 rupees each, it said in a
statement to the Bombay Stock Exchange. The shares slid 2.5
percent to 81.85 rupees.  
 Hindustan Copper Ltd. (HCP IN): Some investment banks in
India are reluctant to participate in the proposed sale of a
government stake in Hindustan Copper on concern that the
company’s share price is too high and will deter investors, the
Economic Times reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares fell 0.2 percent to 511.85 rupees.  
 Hindustan Unilever Ltd. (HUVR IN): India’s biggest
household products maker was cut to “reduce” from “neutral”
by Manish Jain and Anup Sudhendranath, analysts at Nomura
Holdings Inc., who said “heightened” competition and the
company’s focus on regaining lost market share will keep margins
under pressure. The stock dropped 1.6 percent to 255.9 rupees.  
 Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd. (MM IN): India’s largest maker of
sport-utility vehicles was sued by a U.S. dealer, which asked
the Atlanta District Court to prohibit Mahindra from selling in
the U.S. through any other distributor. Global Vehicles USA Inc.
said in its June 14 lawsuit that Mahindra breached a 2006
agreement by twice rejecting its purchase orders for the Mumbai-
based company’s vehicles.  
 Roma Balwani, a spokeswoman for Mahindra, said the lawsuit
and a separate arbitration are without merit and will be
“vigorously contested.”  
 The shares rose 3.5 percent to 629.30 rupees.  
 Reliance Industries Ltd. (RIL IN): India’s largest company
by market value may buy a 26 percent stake in Reliance
Communications Ltd. (RCOM IN), CNBC Awaaz television channel
reported, citing sources it didn’t identify. Reliance Industries
may buy a 26 percent stake in Fortis Healthcare Ltd. (FORH IN),
the Financial Express reported, without saying where it got the
information. A Fortis Healthcare spokesperson denied the report,
the newspaper said. Reliance Industries will buy a majority
stake in GTL Infrastructure Ltd. (GTLI IN), which will in turn
acquire control of Reliance Infratel Ltd., Bloomberg UTV network
reported, without saying where it got the information.  
 Separately, Reliance Industries is considering bidding for
a 4,000 megawatt coal-fired plant in eastern India that may cost
as much as 160 billion rupees ($3.4 billion), said two company
officials briefed on the plan, who declined to be identified
before a decision is taken.  
 Reliance Industries slid 0.8 percent to 1,057.95 rupees.
Reliance Communications added 0.3 percent to 187.30 rupees.
Fortis Healthcare advanced 0.4 percent to 152.1 rupees, GTL
Infrastructure gained 0.4 percent to 152.1 rupees.  
 Tata Steel Ltd. (TATA IN): India’s biggest producer of
alloy can sell shares to its founder Tata Sons Ltd. at a minimum
price of 593.08 rupees apiece, the company’s auditor Deloitte
Haskins & Sells said. The steelmaker on May 27 said it plans to
sell as many as 15 million shares and 12 million warrants to
Tata Sons. The shares fell 1.3 percent to 485.55 rupees.  
